import{_ as t,o,c as a,ag as s}from"./chunks/framework.OsDJF_Ea.js";const p=JSON.parse('{"title":"Module Reference","description":"","frontmatter":{},"headers":[],"relativePath":"modules/index.md","filePath":"modules/index.md"}'),r={name:"modules/index.md"};function n(i,e,l,c,u,d){return o(),a("div",null,[...e[0]||(e[0]=[s('<h1 id="module-reference" tabindex="-1">Module Reference <a class="header-anchor" href="#module-reference" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Module Reference&quot;">​</a></h1><p>The Smart Contact Mic has over 40 modules organized into six categories. Each module has inputs (left side) and outputs (right side) that you connect with cables on the canvas.</p><h2 id="signal-types" tabindex="-1">Signal Types <a class="header-anchor" href="#signal-types" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Signal Types&quot;">​</a></h2><p>There are two signal types in the patcher:</p><ul><li><strong>Audio signals</strong> (green ports) -- These carry the actual sound. They update 44,100 times per second (the sample rate), which is fast enough to represent any audible frequency.</li><li><strong>Control signals</strong> (purple ports) -- These carry values that change parameters over time, typically in a 0 to 1 range. Think of them as invisible hands turning knobs -- an LFO slowly sweeping a filter, or an envelope shaping the volume of a note.</li></ul><p>You can connect audio to control inputs and vice versa, but for best results match signal types.</p><h2 id="categories" tabindex="-1">Categories <a class="header-anchor" href="#categories" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Categories&quot;">​</a></h2><h3 id="sound-sources" tabindex="-1">Sound Sources <a class="header-anchor" href="#sound-sources" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Sound Sources&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Sound sources are where audio begins. Without at least one source module, a patch is silent.</p><p><strong>Synthesis</strong> is the process of creating sound electronically rather than recording it. The simplest form is an <strong>oscillator</strong> -- a module that generates a repeating waveform (like a sine wave, sawtooth, or square wave) at a specific pitch. Different waveform shapes have different tonal qualities: a sine wave is pure and smooth, a sawtooth is bright and buzzy, a square wave is hollow.</p><p>This category also includes <strong>drum synthesis</strong> (creating percussive sounds from scratch rather than playing recordings), <strong>sample playback</strong> (triggering pre-recorded audio files), and <strong>audio input</strong> from the piezo contact mic.</p><h3 id="effects" tabindex="-1">Effects <a class="header-anchor" href="#effects" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Effects&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Effects take an existing sound and transform it. They don&#39;t generate sound on their own -- they need something connected to their input.</p><p>A <strong>filter</strong> removes certain frequencies from a sound. A lowpass filter lets low frequencies through and cuts the highs, making a sound darker or more muffled. Sweeping a filter&#39;s cutoff frequency is one of the most common sounds in electronic music.</p><p>A <strong>VCA</strong> (Voltage Controlled Amplifier) controls volume. On its own that sounds boring, but when you connect an envelope to it, the VCA shapes how a sound fades in and out -- turning a constant tone into a note that starts, sustains, and releases.</p><p><strong>Delay</strong> repeats a sound after a time gap (like an echo). <strong>Reverb</strong> simulates the reflections of a room or space. <strong>Distortion</strong> adds harmonics by overdriving the signal. <strong>Compression</strong> evens out the volume of a signal. Each effect changes the character of the sound passing through it.</p><h3 id="granular-looping" tabindex="-1">Granular / Looping <a class="header-anchor" href="#granular-looping" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Granular / Looping&quot;">​</a></h3><p>These modules manipulate time.</p><p><strong>Granular synthesis</strong> works by chopping audio into tiny fragments called &quot;grains&quot; (typically 10-200 milliseconds long) and playing many of them back simultaneously, often at different pitches, speeds, or positions. The result can range from subtle shimmer to extreme sound transformation. You can freeze a moment of audio and explore it as a texture, or stretch and pitch-shift sounds in ways that conventional effects cannot.</p><p><strong>Loopers</strong> record a passage of audio and play it back in a continuous loop. The simplest use is building up layers -- record a phrase, then play over it while the loop repeats. More advanced loopers let you reverse, speed up, slow down, or slice the recorded audio.</p><p><strong>Recording</strong> modules capture audio to the SD card for later use.</p><h3 id="control" tabindex="-1">Control <a class="header-anchor" href="#control" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Control&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Control modules don&#39;t make sound themselves. They generate signals that change other modules&#39; parameters over time, which is what makes a patch feel alive rather than static.</p><p>An <strong>envelope</strong> (ADSR) produces a shape that rises, falls, and fades when triggered -- like the natural volume curve of a piano key being struck and released. The four stages are Attack (how fast it rises), Decay (how fast it drops to the sustain level), Sustain (the held level), and Release (how fast it fades after you let go).</p><p>An <strong>LFO</strong> (Low Frequency Oscillator) produces a repeating wave, typically too slow to hear as a pitch. Instead, you connect it to a parameter like filter cutoff or volume to create rhythmic movement -- wobble, pulse, sweep.</p><p><strong>Clocks</strong> generate regular timing pulses for sequencers, drum machines, and tempo-synced effects. A <strong>sequencer</strong> steps through a pattern of values in time with a clock, outputting a different pitch or control value on each step.</p><h3 id="hardware-i-o" tabindex="-1">Hardware I/O <a class="header-anchor" href="#hardware-i-o" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Hardware I/O&quot;">​</a></h3><p>These modules connect your patch to the outside world. On the Smart Contact Mic, this means <strong>USB MIDI</strong> for receiving notes and control from a computer or MIDI controller, and the <strong>Stereo Out</strong> module that sends your patch&#39;s audio to the speaker or line output.</p><h3 id="midi-effects" tabindex="-1">MIDI Effects <a class="header-anchor" href="#midi-effects" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;MIDI Effects&quot;">​</a></h3><p>MIDI effect modules process musical note data rather than audio. An <strong>arpeggiator</strong> takes a held chord and plays its notes one at a time in a pattern (up, down, random). A <strong>MIDI looper</strong> records a sequence of notes and plays them back in a loop.</p><h2 id="auto-mapped-modules" tabindex="-1">Auto-Mapped Modules <a class="header-anchor" href="#auto-mapped-modules" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Auto-Mapped Modules&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Some modules automatically assign themselves to hardware banks (shown by a coloured footer on the canvas). These include:</p><ul><li><strong>Stereo Mixer</strong> -- 1-2 banks (volume/mute, pan/solo)</li><li><strong>Drum Machine</strong> -- 2 banks (trigger/pitch, volume/mute)</li><li><strong>Tuned Perc</strong> -- 1 bank (volume/trigger)</li><li><strong>Multi Sample</strong> -- 1 bank (voices/triggers)</li><li><strong>BPM Looper</strong> -- 2 banks (record/mix, randomise/pitch)</li><li><strong>Paralloop</strong> -- 2 banks (record/layer, navigate/mixdown)</li><li><strong>Audio Slicer</strong> -- 3 banks (playback, ADSR, aux send)</li><li><strong>Audio Recorder</strong> -- 1 bank (record/play/navigate)</li><li><strong>Clocks</strong> -- 1 bank (tempo/controls)</li><li><strong>Harmonic Sequencer</strong> -- 1 bank (step values)</li><li><strong>Modal Resonator</strong> -- 1 bank (decay/brightness/pitch/morph)</li></ul>',33)])])}const g=t(r,[["render",n]]);export{p as __pageData,g as default};
